{"cursor":"15582","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist |name = Edmund Brisco \"Henry\" Ford |image = E B Ford.jpg\n|birth_date = |birth_place = Papcastle, Cumberland |death_date = |death_place =\nOxford, Oxfordshire |residence = |citizenship = |nationality = British\n|ethnicity = |field = Ecological genetics |work_institutions = |alma_mater =\nOxford University |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for =\n|influences = |influenced = |prizes = Royal Society's Darwin Medal |religion =\n}} 'Edmund Brisco \"Henry\" Ford' FRS Hon. FRCP (23 April\n1901 â 21 January 1988) was a British ecological geneticist. He was a leader\namong those British biologists who investigated the role of natural selection in\nnature. As a schoolboy Ford became interested in lepidoptera, the group of\ninsects which includes butterflies and moths. He went on to study the genetics\nof natural populations, and invented the field of ecological genetics. Ford was\nawarded the Royal Society's Darwin Medal in 1954. Later, in 1968, he was awarded\nUNESCO's Kalinga Prize for the popularisation of science. {{Cite news |pmid\n= 3279315 |last=Clarke |first=C |publication-date=1988 Mar 3 |year=1988\n|title=Edmund Brisco Ford (1902-1988). |volume=332 |issue=6159\n|periodical=Nature |pages=20 |doi = 10.1038/332020a0 |postscript = }}\n\nFord was born in Papcastle, near Cockermouth, in Cumberland, England, in\n1901. He was educated at Wadham College, Oxford University, graduating in\nzoology in 1924.\n","linknr":301,"url":"E._B._Ford","recorded":1376415838,"links":["/w/index.php?title=E._B._Ford&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=E._B._Ford&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E._B._Ford","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&m